00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:15.380
OREN BOIMAN: What I can say is
there's two parts to the basic

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:18.730
engine that we do in order to
analyze and produce video.

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:23.970
We started from videos
and pixels.

00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:28.170
And in order to do this in video
editing, you need to

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:31.520
move from notions such as pixels
to very high-level

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:35.090
notions, such as characters and
scenes and behaviors and

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:37.140
interactions between
people and objects.

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:39.950
And there might be
pets, whatever.

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:46.690
So the first step that we do
is a step of analysis that,

00:12:46.690 --> 00:12:49.820
using the very sophisticated
technology we have to look for

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:54.244
video understanding, leaves
us with kind of--

00:12:54.244 --> 00:12:57.750
it is a semantic description of
what's going on essentially

00:12:57.750 --> 00:12:59.250
in every frame in the video.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:03.120
But it's not low-level
description, such as things

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:06.250
are moving, but this
is an object.

00:13:06.250 --> 00:13:07.890
This is an important
character.

00:13:07.890 --> 00:13:09.760
He moves from left to right.

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:11.170
The camera's tracking him.

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:12.860
It's doing zoom in, et
cetera, et cetera.

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:17.440
And we manage to use this
metadata in order to decide

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:20.720
what are the important parts of
the video, where we should

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:24.055
focus, how to tell the story,
what parts can we discard from

00:13:24.055 --> 00:13:25.100
the editing.

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:31.700
So the second part of the
algorithm we apply is less

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:34.060
analytical and more--

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:35.830
you can think of
it as an expert

00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:38.300
system of a video editor.

00:13:38.300 --> 00:13:40.330
So this is the creative
part, right?

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:44.450
JEFFREY POSNICK: Which is
historically very difficult to

00:13:44.450 --> 00:13:46.850
codify in an algorithm.

00:13:46.850 --> 00:13:49.460
OREN BOIMAN: And that is a
different domain, right?

00:13:49.460 --> 00:13:53.080
Even with accurate description
of everything that goes on the

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:56.360
video, you still have to decide
how to tell a story.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:13:57.800
That's art.

00:13:57.800 --> 00:13:58.850
That's art and algorithms.

00:13:58.850 --> 00:14:02.740
And then you need to decide
what's the basic information

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:06.910
